<dl id="n29248g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n29" href="#n29248g">N29 (VI.B.21)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n29all.htm#n29248g"> 248(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> John Citizen / Pat Countryman <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n29248g"><li>FW 447.21f </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n29248g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n29248g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n29248g">MS BL 47483-216v</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:402 <a name="qAd11" href="../../ff/fdra/qda.htm#qAd11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/qA/qAd11.htm#n29248g">Draft: III&sect;2A.11</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Joyce&apos;s &lsquo;Pagan&rsquo; (in the text) is an old word fro &lsquo;Countryman&rsquo;. OED:&nbsp;(i) The older sense of classical Latin <i>paganus</i> is &lsquo;of the country, rustic&rsquo; (also as noun). It has been argued that the transferred use reflects the fact that the ancient idolatry lingered on in the rural villages and hamlets after Christianity had been generally accepted in the towns and cities of the Roman Empire; compare Orosius <cite>Histories</cite> 1. Prol. &lsquo;Ex locorum agrestium compitis et pagis pagani vocantur.&rsquo; </mm> </dd></dl>
